) * (1 - ratio)\n\n### Implementation 3:\nThis function calculates how much space is left in each bin after placing the item and uses the sine function to compute the priority. Bins with more space have higher priority.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    space_left = bins - item\n    space_left[space_left < 0] = 0\n    return np.sin(np.pi * space_left / (np.max(bins) + 1))\n\n### Implementation 4:\nThis function uses the difference between the bin size and the item size, combined with the standard deviation of the bins, to compute the priority. Bins that are a good fit for the item have higher priority.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    fit = bins - item\n    fit[fit < 0] = 0\n    return fit * np.std(bins)\n\n### Implementation 5:\nThis function calculates the remaining space in each bin and uses the square root of the space to determine the priority. More space leads to higher priority.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining_space = bins - item\n    remaining_space[remaining_space < 0] = 0\n    return np.sqrt(remaining_space) / np.sqrt(np.max(bins) + 1)\n\n### Implementation 6:\nThis function uses the ratio of the item to the bin size, combined with the cosine function, to determine the priority. Bins that can fit the item have higher priority.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio = item / bins\n    ratio[ratio > 1] = 0\n    return np.cos(np.pi * ratio)\n\n### Implementation 7:\nThis function calculates the remaining space in each bin and uses the exponential function to weight the priority. More space leads to higher priority.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining_space = bins - item\n    remaining_space[remaining_space < 0] = 0\n    return np.exp(remaining_space / (np.max(bins) + 1))\n\n### Implementation 8:\nThis function uses the difference between the bin size and the item size, combined with the logarithm of the bin size, to compute the priority. Bins that are a good fit for the item have higher priority.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    fit = bins - item\n    fit[fit < 0] = 0\n    return np.log(fit + 1) * (1 - np.log(item + 1))\n\n### Implementation 9:\nThis function calculates the ratio of the item to the bin size and uses the sine function to compute the priority. Bins that can fit the item have higher priority.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio = item / bins\n    ratio[ratio > 1] = 0\n    return np.sin(np.pi * ratio)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))#\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (np.std(bins) ** 2)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) \n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))#\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (np.std(bins) ** 2)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(n