for the item.\n\n### Example of a Correct Function:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### How to Generate Unique Functions:\nEach function should combine different allowed operations in a unique way. For example, one might use a combination of exponential and sine functions, another might use logarithms and square roots, etc.\n\n### Final Output:\nYou need to write 10 unique functions, each following the specified format, each using a unique combination of allowed operations.\n\n### How to Ensure Uniqueness:\n- Use different mathematical functions (e.g., log, sqrt, cos, etc.)\n- Combine operations in different ways (e.g., multiplying, adding, etc.)\n- Apply different array operations (e.g., np.mean, np.std, np.exp, etc.)\n- Use different control flows if allowed, but in this case, since control flow is limited, focus on mathematical and array operations.\n</think>\n\n### Solution Code:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * np.sqrt(item * np.mean(bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(np.exp(item) + bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(np.log(item) - np.log(bins)) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp