ed to some ground truth.\n\n### Additional Notes:\n- The functions must be valid Python code.\n- The functions must use the allowed operations only.\n- The functions must not have any syntax errors.\n\n### Example of How to Generate a New Function:\nFor example, one function could be:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) \n\nAnother function could be:\ndef priority(item: float, np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(np.log(item) - np.log(bins)) * np.std(bins) \n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.min(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sqrt(item * np.std(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.min(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sqrt(item * np.std(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item) * np.max(bins) + np.cos(np.pi * item / np.mean(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log1p(item) * np.min(bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / np.std(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.cos(np.pi * item / np.max(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log2(item) * np.min(bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / np.mean(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item) * np.max(bins) + np.cos(np.pi * item / np.mean(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / np.std(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log1p(item) * np.min(bins) + np.cos(np.pi * item / np.max(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.min(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', "def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    for i in range(len(bins)):\n        # This is invalid because it uses a for loop which is not allowed\n        pass\n\n### Constraints:\n- The bins array can have any size >=1.\n- The item can be any float.\n- The bins can have any values, including zero, but in the context of bin packing, bins are containers that can hold items, so typically, bins have a capacity greater than or equal to the item.\n\n### Additional Constraints:\n- The functions must not modify the bins array.\n\n### Final Notes:\n- Each function must be as simple as possible but unique.\n- The functions must be vectorized and efficient.\n\n### Your Task:\nCreate 10 unique functions, each using a different combination of allowed operations, ensuring that each function is unique and produces a unique priority array.\n\n### Thinking Process:\nTo create unique functions, I need to combine different mathematical functions and array operations in various ways. For example, using exp with different terms, combining with sin or cos, using mean, max, min, etc., in different ways. Also, adding or multiplying different terms to get unique expressions.\n\n### Plan:\n1. Use different combinations of exp, sin, cos with various array operations (mean, max, min, etc.).\n2. Try to vary the operations applied to 'item' and 'bins'.\n3. Ensure each function uses a unique combination of operations to produce a distinct priority array.\n\n### Execution:\nI will proceed to create 10 functions, each with a unique combination of the allowed operations, ensuring that each function is valid and meets the requirements.\n\n### Final Answer:\nHere are the 10 unique implementations of the `priority` function:\n\n1. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n2. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n3. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.min(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n4. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n5. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n6. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.min(bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n7. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n8. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n9. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.min(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n10. \ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n</think>\n\nTo solve this problem, we need to generate 10 unique implementations of a Python function named `priority` that serves as a heuristic for optimizing the bin packing problem. The function should take an item size and an array of bins and return an array of priority scores for each bin.\n\n### Approach\nThe approach involves creating vectorized numpy functions that compute the priority score for each bin in a way that is efficient and does not use loops. Each function should use a unique combination of mathematical functions and array operations to ensure uniqueness. The functions should aim to provide a heuristic that can be used to select the best bin for the item based on various criteria such as minimizing loss, maximizing space utilization, or other bin-packing heuristics.\n\n### Solution Code\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.min(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.min(bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.min(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * item) * np.cos(np.pi * item)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) \n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) / (np.std(bins) + 1e-8) + np.cos(np.pi * item / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.log(1 + np.std(bins)) + np.tanh(item / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1)) / (np.mean(bins) + 1e-8) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np