y(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.mean(bins)) * np.log(item / bins + 1) + np.arcsin(np.pi * item / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.mean(bins)) * np.log(item / bins + 1) + np.arccos(np.pi * item / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.sin(item) / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.exp(item - bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # implementation\n    return result\n\n### How to Test the Functions:\nThe functions can be tested in the context of the bin-packing algorithm, but for the purpose of this task, the functions are considered correct as long as they return an array of the same size as bins, with numerical values.\n\n### How to Handle Edge Cases:\nFor bins that are full, the priority could be set to a very low value or zero. For empty bins, the priority could be set to a high value to encourage placing the item there first.\n\n### Suggestion for Edge Cases:\n- For a bin that is already full (bin == capacity), set priority to a very low value.\n- For a remaining space in a bin (capacity - bin), if the item is larger than the remaining space, set priority to zero or a very low value.\n- For a bin that can fit the item, set priority based on some heuristic.\n\n### Additional Suggestion:\nUse mathematical operations to combine multiple factors into the priority score.\n\n### Final Thought:\nEach function should be a valid mathematical expression that combines the item size and the current state of the bins in a unique way to determine the priority.\n\n### Now, the task is to generate 10 such functions, each with a unique combination of operations.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.sin(item) / bins)\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.exp(item - bins)\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item) * np.std(bins) + np.exp(item - np.mean(bins))\n\n### Implementation 4:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.std(bins) + np.exp(item - np.mean(bins))\n\n### Implementation 5:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 6:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item) * np.std(bins) + np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 7:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.std(bins) + np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 8:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.exp(item - bins)\n\n### Implementation 9:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item) * np.std(bins) + np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n'][Process 0] before evaluate_graph[Process 0] after evaluate_graph[Process 0] before evaluate_graph[Process 0] after evaluate_graph[Process 0] before evaluate_graph[Process 0] after evaluate_graph[Process 0] before evaluate_graph[Process 0] after evaluate_graph[Process 0] before evaluate_graph[Process 0] after evaluate_graph[Process 0] before evaluate_graph[Process 0] after evaluate_graph[Process 0] before evaluate_graph[Process 0] aft